83
00:05:39,059 --> 00:05:40,180
called it the mallochio.

84
00:05:40,700 --> 00:05:43,321
This is apotropaic magic, the magic

85
00:05:43,781 --> 00:05:49,343
of warding off evil energies and drawing energies of power inward.

86
00:05:50,282 --> 00:05:56,608
When Dio says, I cry out for magic, he is invoking energy to suffuse everything he makes.

87
00:05:56,948 --> 00:05:59,891
And this is what we can do as we make our games more metal.

88
00:06:00,972 --> 00:06:06,617
If we begin then with the song, the song can be broken down in part to the riff.

89
00:06:23,050 --> 00:06:30,553
A riff is a driving rhythmic motif, a powerful and repeated melody that is instantly memorable

90
00:06:30,773 --> 00:06:31,453
and addictive.

91
00:06:32,213 --> 00:06:38,436
In games, and in game narrative, riffs resemble narrative pacing with steady forward movement

92
00:06:38,696 --> 00:06:45,118
along a critical path, as well as in mechanics, the addictive grind of a repeated core mechanic.

93
00:06:47,758 --> 00:06:53,800
At the same time, the power of the riff is often rooted in dissonant elements, elements

94
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:58,302
which are deliberately grotesque, horrific, disturbing.

95
00:06:58,322 --> 00:07:03,904
The modus diaboli, an interval, either the diminished fifth or the augmented fourth,

96
00:07:03,944 --> 00:07:08,865
depending how you analyze it, which was outlawed by the medieval Christian church because it

97
00:07:08,905 --> 00:07:14,928
was thought to contain pagan energies, erotic energies, the energy of tension.

98
00:07:15,368 --> 00:07:16,888
And you can hear it in this classic.

99
00:07:17,589 --> 00:07:20,230
self-titled song, Black Sabbath.

100
00:07:35,950 --> 00:07:38,933
The Devil's Interval reminds us that sometimes,

101
00:07:39,554 --> 00:07:42,657
elements which deliberately do not fit with our whole,

102
00:07:42,717 --> 00:07:43,759
which clash with it,

103
00:07:44,159 --> 00:07:47,142
can provoke fascination through their contrasts.

104
00:07:48,235 --> 00:07:51,396
And the devil's interval is not the only type of contrast in metal.

105
00:07:51,796 --> 00:07:54,117
Metal revolves around contrast.

106
00:07:54,237 --> 00:07:55,697
It's the essence of its energy.

107
00:07:56,577 --> 00:08:01,139
Riffs provide contrast to solos, bursts of virtuosic, often

108
00:08:01,299 --> 00:08:08,061
neoclassically influenced melody, as in this moment from Bloody Tears

109
00:08:08,401 --> 00:08:11,722
from the soundtrack of Castlevania II, Simon's Quest.

110
00:08:31,884 --> 00:08:38,427
And you can hear it, that delicate beauty amid the violence and the horror of the riff.

111
00:08:40,145 --> 00:08:45,126
Once the song is firmly in place, the song spawns the word.

112
00:08:45,727 --> 00:08:49,567
It can inspire lyrics and other verbal elements.

113
00:08:50,348 --> 00:08:54,209
The song is generative in the sense of procedural generation

114
00:08:54,589 --> 00:08:56,509
and different types of metal will inspire

115
00:08:56,949 --> 00:08:59,070
different lyrical flights of fancy,

116
00:08:59,130 --> 00:09:02,510
whether it is the high fantasy of power metal

117
00:09:02,951 --> 00:09:07,932
with much soaring triumphantly on the backs of unicorns

118
00:09:08,392 --> 00:09:09,892
or whether it's more doom metal.

119
00:09:10,492 --> 00:09:13,354
reveling in brutality and the grotesque.

120
00:09:16,415 --> 00:09:22,577
One example of this potential of the song to generate the word,

121
00:09:22,597 --> 00:09:27,859
to spawn the word, is Paradise Lost, John Milton's Paradise Lost,

122
00:09:28,199 --> 00:09:31,721
which in some sense is the ultimate metal poem.

123
00:09:31,741 --> 00:09:36,503
And you can see the generative power of Milton's epic poem,

124
00:09:36,683 --> 00:09:37,863
which he regarded as song.

125
00:09:38,704 --> 00:09:44,049
in a random Twitter bot tweeting lines from various books of Paradise Lost,

126
00:09:44,150 --> 00:09:49,255
and any one of those lines could serve as the title for a metal album,

127
00:09:50,056 --> 00:09:53,780
or part of it could be used as a metal band, or even...

128
00:09:54,801 --> 00:10:00,064
The dialogue or item descriptions from a metal-inspired game.

129
00:10:00,524 --> 00:10:06,488
Into this wild abyss the weary fiend stood on the brink of hell and looked a while,

130
00:10:06,968 --> 00:10:10,571
